Here is an example of a dictionary in C# that maps strings to floats:

```csharp
Dictionary<string, float> myDictionary = new Dictionary<string, float>();
```

You can add key-value pairs to this dictionary like so:

```csharp
myDictionary.Add("key1", 1.0f);
myDictionary.Add("key2", 2.0f);
// Add more key-value pairs as needed
```

To access a specific value from the dictionary, you can do:

```csharp
float value = myDictionary["key1"];
```

Remember to include `using System.Collections.Generic;` at the beginning of the C# file to be able to use `Dictionary`.

If you want to have a dictionary where the values are arrays of floats instead of just individual floats, you can use the following code in C#:

```csharp
Dictionary<string, float[]> myDictionary = new Dictionary<string, float[]>();
```

Here's how you can add values to this dictionary:

```csharp
float[] array1 = new float[] { 1.0f, 2.0f, 3.0f };
float[] array2 = new float[] { 4.0f, 5.0f };

myDictionary.Add("key1", array1);
myDictionary.Add("key2", array2);
// Add more key-value pairs as needed
```

You can access a specific array of floats using the key in the dictionary like this:

```csharp
float[] values = myDictionary["key1"];
```

Each value in the dictionary is an array of floats.
